Collect a **dotnet-trace** with the `HttpHandlerDiagnosticListener` events and HTTP event counters:

```bash
# Install the tool if needed
dotnet tool install -g dotnet-trace

# Collect HttpClient events + counters
dotnet-trace collect \
  -p <PID> \
  --providers "System.Net.Http,Microsoft-Diagnostics-DiagnosticSource:::FilterAndPayloadSpecs=[AS]System.Net.Http.HttpRequestOut@Activity1Start:-Request.RequestUri;Request.Method,\
[AS]System.Net.Http.HttpRequestOut@Activity1Stop:-StatusCode;Duration"
```

**Key things this gives you:**
- **Request URI & method** for every outbound call
- **Status code** (so you can filter for 500s)
- **Duration** of each request

**To analyze**, open the `.nettrace` file in Visual Studio, PerfView, or [Speedscope](https://www.speedscope.app). Filter events by `StatusCode == 500`.

**Alternatively**, if you want a lighter-weight approach, add logging directly:

```csharp
// In Program.cs — add a delegating handler
builder.Services.AddHttpClient("downstream", c =>
{
    c.BaseAddress = new Uri("https://api.example.com");
})
.AddHttpMessageHandler(() => new LoggingHandler());

// Simple handler
public class LoggingHandler : DelegatingHandler
{
    protected override async Task<HttpResponseMessage> SendAsync(
        HttpRequestMessage req, CancellationToken ct)
    {
        var sw = Stopwatch.StartNew();
        var resp = await base.SendAsync(req, ct);
        sw.Stop();

        if (!resp.IsSuccessStatusCode)
            Log.Warning("{Method} {Uri} → {Status} in {Ms}ms",
                req.Method, req.RequestUri, (int)resp.StatusCode, sw.ElapsedMilliseconds);

        return resp;
    }
}
```

**Recommendation:** Start with `dotnet-trace` since it requires no code changes and you can attach to the running process. Switch to the handler approach if you need persistent structured logging for dashboards/alerts.
